metadata.name: Dencity #731
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Hexagones - Art for Bots #4
metadata.description:
Not for Humans.

Sometimes after rapid drops, bots are set up to watch for blockchain contracts and activity, often getting in on the action before people with wallets and using UI front-ends can. Price your drop too low, and the bots will scoop everything up before anyone has seen anything.

Sometimes we make art for the bots. They wait, watch, and buy and flip before moving on, indifferent to what they see and do. These (coincidentally Twitter icon orientated) hexagons will make the bots hearts go [beep] [boop], before becoming hexagones.

Instructions ::

h - toggle high-res
s - download and save image

metadata.name: Growth v02 #20
metadata.description:
Growth patterns, version 2. January 2022
Edition of 512

Growth v02 is an generative exploration of patterns in the style of William Morris' iconic wallpaper designs from the 1800s. The code for the Growth series was originally designed to create plausible road networks but has been rewritten to create more organic curved forms. Created with p5js.

'space' to pause the simulation
'h' to toggle to higher res (increases canvas size but runs slower: great for screengrabs)
'r' to reset the seed (some features are locked to the original hash)
's' to save an image to disk
All generated patterns are tile-able horizontally and vertically.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

This project relies heavily on randomly generated values. It has been thoroughly tested. However, there is always the chance that the wrong combination of randomness can create less-compelling growth. If you feel you version is not living up to the potential promised with this piece, please email me.

metadata.name: Kintsugi #91
metadata.description:
Kintsugi is a philosophy, it's the concept of highlighting imperfections, visualizing patches and seams on the area to focus on, rather than focusing on missing details.

This art of precious scars is a technique used as a means of analyzing the idea of ‚Äã‚Äãloss through synthesis and restoration of the destroyed and a metaphor for the possibility of rebirth.
Recovery from destructive events is possible through care and patching, not through hiding the damage, but by accepting a new state of the object or the whole life.
The world is a vase that is endlessly disassembled and sewn together again, continuing to bear traces of each event.

Non-human entities helped us put these vases together. In the beginning, there were vague forms, these were the shards themselves, created in collaboration with Latent Diffusion. Over time, they have grown in detail, drawing their stories more clearly, thanks to Jax Diffusion.

The code that puts everything together was written by Yulikolay, for which he is greatly appreciated.

metadata.name: Swatches #19
metadata.description:
Swatches is the first generative token project by Paul Drzal.

Like photography gels scattered on the light table, the layers combine to create the composition.  A random four-color palette in varying opacities creates your swatch, hand pulled on the screen.

Colors are inspired by the bold stylized drawings of architects Wes Jones and Neil Denari.

Press ‚Äòs‚Äô to save your Swatch.  Zoom out and refresh to save a larger file.

Generative visual composition, hybrid techniques, interactive, textures source created with GAN, assist by AI, eclectic, colors, transform in autonomous system, glitch, made with code, and modular patch.

metadata.name: Colored Elementary Cellular Automaton #429
metadata.description:
The algorithm is based on Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton. 
This is a 1D cellular automaton with a neighborhood of 5 cells. This gives us 2^5 = 32 patterns for a neighborhood and 2^32 = 4.29B possible combinations!!! The size of the cell varies in a range of 2 to 8. There is a 15% of getting a black and white art.

Pattern rarity:
- Pattern 1 _25%
- Pattern 2 _30%
- Pattern 3 _35%
- Pattern 4 _15%

Note: The art might look in different resolutions because of the responsive view, but the color, pattern, and layout remain the same.

metadata.name: contrapuntos #409
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.
